Growing populations, Expanding challenges

Understand the impact of population growth on global development.

Author

Marie Kolibas

Published

April 27, 2025

From 2.1% in 1960 to just 0.9% in 2023, the worldâs population growth rate has more than halved in 6 decades.

In the collective imagination, strong demographic growth is often seen as a driver of economic dynamism. But is this always the case? A fast-growing population can also put pressure on infrastructures, natural resources and public services, creating development inequalities.

This analysis explores global demographic trends and highlights the links between growth rates, GDP, life expectancy and access to healthcare, offering a data-driven view of the challenges and opportunities associated with population change.

A global slowdown trend

While the global growth rate is steadily declining, this slowdown is not uniform from one continent to the next, as we shall see.

The bar chart shows how global growth dynamics have gradually shifted towards a handful of regions, highlighting growing regional disparities in population trends.

Where is population increasing the most?

A demographic divide is emerging: While many developing countries continue to grow rapidly, most developed nations are slowing down or even regressing.

Countries such as Russia and China are now showing negative growth, marking a turning point in global demographic trends.

This growing imbalance raises important questions about the future: How will societies adapt to aging populations, changing workforces and uneven demographic pressures?

Healthier nations, slower growth: A global demographic shift

In the 1970s, the link between population growth and life expectancy was scattered. Some high-growth countries had decent life expectancies, while others lagged behind, highlighting uneven development.Â Limited access to healthcare did not seem to slow growth in many regions.

In recent years, the trend has been reversed: countries with low population growth tend to live longer.Â Regions with better healthcare also have lower fertility rates, suggesting a deeper demographic transition.

This suggests a global shift: Better access to healthcare is no longer just a matter of survival,Â itâs associated with lower fertility, better planning and longer life.

These two dimensions combined highlight a key point: Investment in healthcare infrastructure not only saves lives, but also shapes demographic trends.

What does the future hold for the worldâs demographics?

As we enter the next few decades, the demographic landscape is changing rapidly, with some countries facing rapid growth, while others are confronted with ageing and decline.

Key findings:

  • Global slowdown in population growth, with strong regional contrasts.

  • Life expectancy is closely linked to wealth and access to healthcare.

  • Developing countries need to adapt their infrastructures to their growth.

  • Developed nations face aging populations and a shrinking workforce.

This evolution has an impact not only on economies and societies, but also on the environment: growth strains resources, while decline could enable more sustainable planning.
